Lab 4: KNN regression

Write a function myknn() to perform KNN regression on a data set with two columns – one for the predictor and one for the response.

Inputs to your function should be:

  • dat = data.frame with two columns
  • name.x = name of predictor column
  • name.y = name of response column
  • k = the K in KNN

Your function should return yhat = vector of predicted \(y\) values for each \(x\) value in column name.x.

The steps below tell how to test myknn().

  1. Fit an SLR model on the advertising data using TV as the predictor and sales as the response. Make a scatter plot of the data and the fitted SLR line. Compute the MSE for the SLR model. \[ MSE = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat f(x_i))^2= \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat y_i)^2\]
library(dplyr)
library(FNN)
advertising <- read.csv("~/Desktop/stat5310/week13/Advertising.csv", row.names=1)
##fit SLR model
TV.mod <- lm(sales~TV, data=advertising)

##make a scatter plot
plot(sales~TV, data=advertising, pch=19, col=6); abline(TV.mod, col=1, lwd=2)


##compute MSE for SLR model
MSE <- mean(TV.mod$residuals^2)
MSE
[1] 10.51265
  1. Use myknn() to fit three KNN models to the same data using \(k\) values 3,9, and 27. Compute the MSE for each \(k\) value and overlay each of the resulting yhat vectors on the scatter plot in a different color. Add a legend.
## write a function

myknn <- function(dat, name.x, name.y, k) {

dat <- dat[order(dat[,name.x]),]

yhat <- NULL

for(i in 1:nrow(dat)){
x0 <- dat[, name.x][i]
dat$d0 <- abs(dat[,name.x] - x0)
yi <- dat %>% arrange(d0) %>% head(k) %>% select(name.y) %>% unlist() %>% mean()
yhat <- c(yhat, yi)


}
return(yhat)

}

  1. Make a data.frame with the following columns: predictor, k, MSE(SLR), and MSE(KNN). This data.frame should be 6x4 where 6 = [2 predictors (TV or radio)] \(\times\) [3 k values (3,9,27)].
## make a data frame
df <- data.frame(predictor = c(rep("TV", 3), rep("radio", 3)),

  1. Bonus problem (10 points): Modify myknn() so that it uses leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV). Call the new function myknn.cv(). It should return yhat.cv = vector of predicted \(y\) values based on the leave-one-out approach. You decide how to test myknn.cv().
myknn.cv <- function(dat, name.x, name.y, k) {

dat <- dat[order(dat[,name.x]),]

yhat.cv <- NULL

for(i in 1:nrow(dat)){
x0 <- dat[, name.x][i]
dat$d0 <- abs(dat[,name.x] - x0)
yi <- dat[-i,] %>% arrange(d0) %>% head(k) %>% select(name.y) %>% unlist() %>% mean()
yhat.cv <- c(yhat.cv, yi)

}
return(yhat.cv)
}
